&gt; _&quot;... I&#39;m pretty new to triple nested loops ...&quot;_

They are not too common, I find that most data can be parsed with just 1 or 2 loops.

&gt; _&quot;... I&#39;m aware the first loop is for rows, the second for columns and the third is for the values of the columns. ...&quot;_

The third loop is not technically required; use the _[String#repeat](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#repeat(int))_ method.

You&#39;ll need two _[iterative for-loops](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iteration)_, and two variables to hold values.  
Iterate on _n_, then iterate on _n&amp;minus;&amp;Delta;n_.
- _n_ for the amount of tokens
- _&amp;Delta;n_ for the decrease in tokens, and token length

Here is an example.

```java
String string(char letter, int n) {
    StringBuilder string = new StringBuilder();
    String newline = System.lineSeparator();
    char copy;
    int n1 = n;
    for (int i = 0, j; i &lt; n; i++) {
        if (i != 0) string.append(newline);
        copy = letter;
        for (j = 0; j &lt; n1; j++) {
            if (j != 0) string.append(&#39; &#39;);
            if (copy - 1 == &#39;Z&#39;) copy = &#39;A&#39;;
            string.append(String.valueOf(copy++).repeat(n - j));
        }
        n1--;
    }
    return string.toString();
}
```

